I apologize for the confusion. If you plan to package the application as a JAR file and run it inside a directory, the directory structure will be relative to the location of the JAR file.

Let's assume you have packaged your application as `template-app.jar`. When you run the JAR file using the command `java -jar template-app.jar` inside a directory, let's say `/path/to/directory`, the directory structure will be created relative to `/path/to/directory`.

Here's an updated version of the code that creates the folders relative to the JAR file location:

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.nio.file.*;
import java.util.Properties;

public class MainClass {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Get the current directory where the JAR file is located
        String currentDirectory = System.getProperty("user.dir");

        // Create folders
        File srcDir = new File(currentDirectory + File.separator + "template-project" + File.separator + "src");
        srcDir.mkdirs();

        File resourceDir = new File(currentDirectory + File.separator + "template-project" + File.separator + "resources");
        resourceDir.mkdirs();

        File testDir = new File(currentDirectory + File.separator + "template-project" + File.separator + "tests");
        testDir.mkdirs();

        // Create config file
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.setProperty("key", "value");

        File configFile = new File(currentDirectory + File.separator + "template-project" + File.separator + "config.properties");
        try (OutputStream output = new FileOutputStream(configFile)) {
            props.store(output, "Config Properties");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        // Generate pom.xml file
        String pomXmlContent = "<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n" +
                               "<project>\n" +
                               "  <groupId>com.example</groupId>\n" +
                               "  <artifactId>template-project</artifactId>\n" +
                               "  <version>1.0.0</version>\n" +
                               "</project>";

        File pomXmlFile = new File(currentDirectory + File.separator + "template-project" + File.separator + "pom.xml");
        try (PrintWriter writer = new PrintWriter(pomXmlFile)) {
            writer.println(pomXmlContent);
        } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

In this updated code, we are using `System.getProperty("user.dir")` to get the current directory where the JAR file resides. We then use this directory as the base to create the relative folder structure.

For example, if the JAR file is located at `/path/to/directory/template-app.jar`, running the JAR file will create the folder structure under `/path/to/directory/template-project/`.

Please note that when you package your application as a JAR file, the resulting folder structure will be relative to the location of the JAR file, not the location where you run the JAR file from.
